{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/725"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.03,0.51,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"333"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9076"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47181"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 78-year-old Australian man who is usually otherwise well presents with a two-day history of central colicky abdominal pain that has gradually become worse. His abdomen has become distended and he has now started vomiting green stained fluid. He has not opened his bowels for four days and has not passed any flatus in the last 24 hours. His bowel movements are usually regular, with no haematochezia nor melaena. His weight and appetite have been stable for some time, although in the past few days he has felt nauseated and not tolerated much oral intake. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and hypertension. He has never had any surgical procedures. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, pulse 90/min and regular, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C.  His abdomen is distended but soft with no guarding or rigidity, with high-pitched bowel sounds on auscultation. A plain abdominal X-ray shows dilated loops of small intestine and air within the region of the biliary tree.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his present problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholangiocarcinoma","Liver abscess","Cholelithiasis","Cholangitis","Incisional hernia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has clinical and radiological features consistent with a small bowel obstruction, including central colicky pain, early bilious vomiting, obstipation, abdominal distension and tinkling bowel sounds, with dilated loops of small bowel on the X-ray. In a patient without previous abdominal surgery, a hernial obstruction is possible, but the gas in the biliary tree (pneumobilia) suggests another cause. Pneumobilia is the result of either infection by gas-forming organisms in the portal venous system and/or free communication of the biliary tree with the gut.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe commonest explanations for pneumobilia include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Echolangitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eliver abscess with communication to the biliary tree\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Espontaneous biliary-enteric fistula from gallstone ileus or cholangiocarcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erecent biliary instrumentation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe last is the most common explanation for pneumobilia and can be the result of recent biliary instrumentation with endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) or sphincterotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has not had an ERCP and is not overtly septic: if liver abscess were the culprit, the patient would be expected to have right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, unintentional weight loss and more prolonged nausea and anorexia. Likewise, the patient does not appear to have cholangitis, which is characterised by the present of Charcot\u2019s triad: fever, jaundice and right upper quadrant pain, none of which is noted in this case. With cholangiocarcinoma, the clinical picture would include jaundice, weight loss and anorexia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESo this case suggests a small bowel obstruction with a communication to the bowel. The most likely cause is therefore gallstone ileus. ie the underlying problem has been \u003Cstrong\u003Echolelithiasis.\u003C/strong\u003E There has been a fistulous communication between the gallbladder and the gut, with an eroding gallstone passing into the small bowel, where it has become obstructed. Air from the gut can enter the biliary tree through the cholecysto-duodenal fistula. A CT scan would help distinguish portal venous gas from pneumobilia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gallstone ileus is an uncommon, but well recognised cause of small bowel obstruction."],"references":["Sherman, SC \u0026 Tran, H 2006, \u2018Pneumobilia: benign or life-threatening\u2019, The Journal of Emergency Medicine, vol. 30, no. 2, pp. 147\u2013153, viewed 20 April 2021, \u003Chttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16567248/\u003E.","Scott, TM 2017, What are Charcot\u2019s triad and Reynolds pentad in acute cholangitis?, Medscape, viewed 20 April 2021, \u003Chttps://www.medscape.com/answers/774245-75976/what-are-charcots-triad-and-reynolds-pentad-in-acute-cholangitis\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"725"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T15:13:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T15:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"725"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114948"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude